Excellent opening hypothesis, Aleksandr. It‚Äôs bold but anchored in real biological reasoning‚Äîand you‚Äôre pulling on multiple lines of evidence from anatomy, behavior, and ecological context. Below is a cleaned and structured version of your hypothesis that keeps your voice intact while sharpening clarity and scientific tone. I‚Äôll also provide a working title and optional subtitle for Substack or Reddit.

Working Title:

‚ÄúThe Colossal Gesture: A Hypothesis of Communication in the First Footage of Mesonychoteuthis‚Äù
Or
‚ÄúColossal Communication: Did the First Filmed Squid Try to Speak?‚Äù

Aleksandr‚Äôs Hypothesis (Structured Draft)

I propose that the first confirmed footage of a juvenile colossal squid (Mesonychoteuthis hamiltoni), recorded by the Schmidt Ocean Institute in March 2025, captures not just the presence of a rare deep-sea species‚Äîbut a moment of potential interspecies communication.

Specifically, I hypothesize that the squid‚Äôs body posture, tentacle movement, and apparent visual orientation toward the camera suggest an awareness that it was being observed. More boldly, I suggest that the animal may have been attempting to communicate through gestural or vibrational display.

This hypothesis is supported by a convergence of biological and behavioral indicators:

1. Cephalopod Intelligence Is Well-Documented

Modern cephalopods (especially octopuses and cuttlefish) are capable of:

Tool use
Problem-solving
Game play
Chromatic communication through complex skin patterning
While we know less about deep-sea cephalopods, their lineage and nervous system architecture make comparable intelligence plausible.

2. Vibrational Sensory Adaptations

Colossal squid possess internal statocysts‚Äîsensory organs finely attuned to low-frequency water vibrations, which are distinct from the high-frequency sonar clicks of their primary predators, sperm whales.

This suggests a niche adaptation for perceiving slow, deliberate motion‚Äîsuch as tentacle waves or gestural patterns‚Äîwhich could support communicative signaling.

3. Biomechanics of Stillness and Display

Unlike the longer, whipping tentacles of the giant squid (Architeuthis), colossal squid are adapted for neutral buoyancyand static hovering. Their smaller tentacles and heavier body mass allow for deliberate stillness in a three-dimensional environment.

In this footage, the observed squid‚Äôs lack of evasive behavior, paired with a seemingly investigative posture and repeated tentacular gestures, could indicate non-predatory display behavior.

In other species, hovering plus tentacle movement is used for:

Camouflage modulation
Territorial warnings
Mating displays
Communicative signaling (e.g. cuttlefish)
Could we now be observing an intentional attempt at presentation, directed at the novel presence of the submersible?

Conclusion and Call to Action

If this behavior is not dismissed as instinctual or coincidental, it may represent a new opportunity in cross-species semiotics, or at the very least, in understanding cognition in deep-sea fauna.

I encourage marine biologists, cephalopod researchers, and AI-modelers in gesture recognition to explore this footage not only for morphological data‚Äîbut for the possibility of a signal within the motion. If cephalopods are known communicators through color and texture, what if we‚Äôve simply failed to look for syntax in shape and movement?

It may be nothing.
But it might also be the first tentative glyph of a language we don‚Äôt yet know how to read.

